<DOC><DOCNO> AP900924-0270 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-09-24-90 1332EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AP-Gold     09-24 0268</FIRST><SECOND>Dollar-Gold, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0013,0307</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Down; Gold Up</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with late European prices and rates plusearly afternoon New York quotes.</NOTE><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar fell against all the major currenciesin European trading today, hurt by perceptions that majorindustrialized nations may let the U.S. currency decline further.   Gold prices rose.   The Group of Seven ministers issued a statement over the weekendcalling for continued firm monetary policies in the face of highoil prices, which are stoking inflation.   The statement also expressed contentment with recent movementsin currency values.   The Tokyo markets were closed for Autumnal Equinox Day.   In London, the dollar fell to a closing 135.57 Japanese yen from137.33 yen at Friday's Tokyo close. The dollar fetched 136.30 yenin early afternoon trading in New York.   The British pound rose in London to $1.8810 from $1.8465 lateFriday. A pound was quoted at $1.8805 in the early afternoon in NewYork.   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday'slevels, were: 1.5565 German marks, down from 1.5770; 1.2965 Swissfrancs, down from 1.3205; 5.2145 French francs, down from 5.2790;1.7665 Dutch guilders, down from 1.7773; 1,165.50 Italian lire,down from 1,175.75; and 1.1501 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1528.   Selected rates for the dollar in the early afternoon in New Yorkincluded: 1.5585 German marks; 1.2985 Swiss francs; 1.1531 Canadiandollars; and 1,168.20 Italian lire.   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $396.55 a troy ounce from$388.25 late Friday. In Zurich, the metal rose to a closing bid of$392.90 from $392.20 late Friday. Earlier, in Hong Kong gold rose$1.05 to close at a bid of $389.42.   Silver bullion rose in London to a late bid of $4.89 a troyounce from $4.81 late Friday.</TEXT></DOC>